"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Samuel chapters 19–21
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2samuel-19-21.py

Historical/ANE context, canonical function, Second Temple reception:

Ch19: David's return after Absalom — grief vs. Joab's rebuke; tribal politics
      (Judah/Israel split presaged); Shimei's pardon; Mephibosheth vindicated;
      Barzillai's loyalty; seeds of the north-south divide (vv40-43)
Ch20: Sheba's revolt — Benjaminite resistance; Joab's murder of Amasa;
      the wise woman of Abel Beth-maacah; administrative list of David's court
Ch21: Blood-guilt, famine, and Gibeonite atonement; Rizpah's vigil;
      David buries Saul's bones; Philistine giants (Rephaim remnants)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>The news reaches Joab that 'the king is weeping and mourning for Absalom.' The juxtaposition is stark: v1 reports the military intelligence (victory) while simultaneously reporting the king's response (grief). The gap between the army's triumph and David's mourning is the dramatic fulcrum of the chapter. In ancient Near Eastern battle culture, the king's public response to victory was expected to be ceremonial — public grief for the enemy (even a traitorous son) was politically destabilizing, as Joab makes plain in vv5-7. David's grief is theologically authentic (he loved Absalom, 18:5, 33) but politically destructive.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The victory becomes mourning (<em>tĕbûʾāh</em>, the 'result/produce' of the day) for all the people when they hear the king's state. The reversal of the expected emotional register — the survivors of a victorious battle slipping back like a defeated army (v3) — illustrates how tightly the ancient Israelite community was bound to its king's public demeanor. The army fought for David, not for an abstract national interest; his grief for Absalom negates their sacrifice in their eyes.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'The people crept back into the city that day like soldiers slipping in under cover of shame after a rout in battle.' The simile draws on the specific shame of military defeat — soldiers who have lost (<em>hit-ḥabbēʾ</em>, to hide/steal away) return without the normal victory celebrations. The psychological accuracy of the simile is notable: these are victorious soldiers who feel defeated because their king treats the battle's outcome as a personal catastrophe. The narrative's realism about military morale is striking.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David's lament — 'O my son Absalom! O Absalom, my son, my son!' — is the most repeated formula of parental grief in the OT (the threefold repetition appears in 18:33 as well). The covering of the king's face is a mourning gesture (cf. Esther 7:8, where Haman's face is covered before execution; 2 Sam 15:30, where David covered his face in the Absalom flight). In the Akkadian lament tradition, the king's covered face symbolizes the withdrawal of divine favor from the realm — the public visibility of the mourning is culturally appropriate but politically disabling.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Joab's rebuke is the most direct confrontation between a subordinate and the king in the Samuel narratives. 'Today you have shamed (<em>bōšet</em>) all your servants' — the language of honor (<em>kābôd</em>) and shame (<em>bōšet</em>) governs ancient Israelite social relations. Joab argues that David has inverted the honor structure: those who risked their lives for the king are shamed, while those who threatened his life are honored (Absalom). The rebuke is politically necessary and personally courageous; it also establishes Joab's pragmatic loyalty in tension with his moral compromises elsewhere.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Loving those who hate you and hating those who love you.' Joab's accusation formulates the inversion in theological language: the love/hate vocabulary is covenantal (<em>ʾāhab</em>/<em>śānēʾ</em> — the same terms used in Deuteronomic covenant language for loyalty/disloyalty). Joab is accusing David of treating covenant relations backwards: those whose <em>ḥesed</em> to David should be rewarded (his men) are being rejected, while the rebel who violated covenant is being mourned. This connects to the broader DH theme: covenantal loyalty structures must be maintained even at personal emotional cost.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Joab's ultimatum — 'I swear by YHWH, if you do not go out, not a man will remain with you tonight' — is technically insubordination but functionally necessary crisis management. The oath formula (<em>kî im</em> + divine oath) establishes the gravity of the threat: this is not an exaggeration but a calculated political forecast. The historical result (Sheba's revolt in ch20, which nearly repeats the Absalom split) validates Joab's warning. David's compliance (v8) shows he grasps the political reality, even if his grief is not immediately resolved.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David sitting in the gate (<em>yôšēb baššaʿar</em>) is the legally and politically significant act: the gate was the site of judicial proceedings, commercial transactions, and royal audiences (Ruth 4:1-12; 2 Sam 15:2). By sitting in the gate David reassumes his public judicial function — the visible act of royal presence that the rebellion had suspended. The people's response ('all the people came before the king') indicates immediate political restoration: the simple act of the king taking his judicial seat restores order.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The tribal debate throughout Israel — 'The king rescued us from our enemies... but he fled the country because of Absalom' — captures the political complexity of the post-rebellion moment. The people credit David with the Philistine victories (the 'enemies' of v9) but note that he fled before Absalom. The restoration debate is entirely pragmatic: not 'is David the LORD's anointed?' but 'why has no one taken steps to bring the king back?' The question reveals that the restoration required popular initiative, not just David's willingness — the king must be re-invited.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Absalom, whom we anointed over us, is dead in battle.' This verse openly states what the narrative had left implicit: the people of Israel had anointed Absalom (<em>māšaḥnû</em>). The anointing of Absalom — likely a formal ceremony in Hebron (15:10-12, though the anointing there is implied rather than explicit) — was an act of de facto recognition as king. Its failure means Israel is now kingless, having abandoned their legitimate king. The political vacuum makes restoration urgent.</p>",
    "11": "<p>David's message through Zadok and Abiathar to the elders of Judah — 'Why should you be the last to bring the king back?' — reveals the political paradox of the restoration: Judah, David's own tribe, is slowest to move. This may reflect Judah's deeper involvement in the Absalom rebellion (Absalom had crowned himself at Hebron, in Judah, 15:10), making them more politically cautious. The use of priests as political intermediaries reflects the sacral authority that legitimized the message.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'You are my kinsmen — my own bone and flesh.' David appeals to tribal kinship (<em>ʿaṣmî ûḇĕśārî</em>, my bone and my flesh) as the ground of obligation. This is the kinship-covenant formula that appears in Gen 2:23 (Adam and Eve), 29:14 (Laban and Jacob), and 2 Sam 5:1 (all Israel to David at Hebron). By invoking the bone-and-flesh formula, David appeals to the tribal solidarity that should have kept Judah loyal throughout — the implication being that abandonment of their bone-and-flesh king requires explanation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The appointment of Amasa as commander in place of Joab is both a political olive branch to Absalom's former supporters (Amasa had commanded Absalom's army, 17:25) and a personal punishment for Joab's insubordination in killing Absalom against orders (18:5, 14). Amasa is David's nephew (through Abigail's sister Zeruiah or Abigail daughter of Nahash — the genealogies in 17:25 and 1 Chr 2:16-17 are variant). The appointment proves to be a political miscalculation: Amasa is slow to mobilize (20:5) and Joab murders him (20:10).</p>",
    "14": "<p>'He won over the hearts of all the men of Judah as one man' — <em>wayyaṭ ləḇab kol ʾîš Yĕhûdāh kĕʾîš ʾeḥād</em>. The 'one man' idiom (<em>kĕʾîš ʾeḥād</em>) appears in the Judges tradition to describe unified tribal action (Judg 20:1, 8, 11 — Israelite assembly's unanimous response to Gibeah). Its use here signals that David achieved the tribal consensus necessary for legitimate restoration. The political achievement — moving Judah from the last to bring the king back (v11) to unanimous support — required the Amasa appointment as the price of reconciliation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The king's arrival at the Jordan and Judah's presence at Gilgal to escort him across is historically and symbolically significant. Gilgal was the first encampment after the Jordan crossing in Joshua's conquest (Josh 4:19-20) — the site where Israel's covenant with YHWH was renewed by circumcision (Josh 5:2-9) and where the conquest memorial stones were set up. David's return through Gilgal mirrors Joshua's initial entry: the anointed leader crosses the Jordan at the covenant-renewal site. The DH's use of Gilgal as a theologically loaded location (also 1 Sam 11:15; 15:12-33) makes this crossing resonant.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Shimei son of Gera the Benjaminite rushes to meet the returning king. This is the man who cursed David during the Absalom flight (16:5-8), throwing stones and calling him 'a man of blood' and 'worthless man' (<em>ʾîš haddāmîm</em> and <em>ʾîš habbəliyyaʿal</em>). His urgency now — 'hurried down... to meet King David' — reflects the reversal of political fortunes: the king whose downfall Shimei celebrated has now triumphed. The political calculation of submitting early (before the king crosses the Jordan) mirrors general ancient Near Eastern amnesty conventions: those who submitted first received better terms.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The thousand Benjaminites accompanying Shimei represent his tribe's communal submission — not merely personal apology but a corporate statement. Ziba the servant of Saul's household (whose manipulation of the Mephibosheth situation David must now adjudicate, vv24-29) is also present with his household. The convergence of these politically compromised individuals at the Jordan crossing forces David to make public decisions about mercy and justice under the scrutiny of the entire assembly.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'They crossed the ford to help bring the king's household over' — the practical service of ferrying the king's household across the Jordan is itself an act of political submission. Shimei's falling down before the king (<em>wayyippōl lipenê haMMelek</em>) and his appeal to the king's mercy follow the standard supplication protocol: prostration, verbal appeal, and implicit acknowledgment of the king's judicial authority over his fate. The timing — crossing before the king — ensures maximum visibility for his submission.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Shimei's petition — 'May my lord not hold me guilty or remember the wrong your servant did' — uses the judicial vocabulary of guilt-memory: <em>zākar</em> (remember) in the context of covenant implies judicial action based on remembered offense. The king's memory of wrong is what triggers punishment; Shimei appeals for the memory to be annulled. This is consistent with ancient Near Eastern royal amnesty conventions in which the monarch's formal declaration of non-remembrance constituted legal pardon.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'I have come today, the first of all the house of Joseph.' 'House of Joseph' here means all the northern tribes (Ephraim and Manasseh), not Judah. Shimei's claim to be first of the northern tribes to submit is a political statement: he represents himself as leading the north's reconciliation with David. The claim may be accurate (he crossed before others) and is strategically calculated to earn maximum credit for early submission — the first-comer in reconciliation narratives always receives special recognition.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abishai's demand for Shimei's execution — 'Should not Shimei be put to death? He cursed YHWH's anointed' — applies the strict legal principle of lèse-majesté: cursing the king is a capital offense (cf. Lev 24:11-16 for cursing God; 1 Kgs 21:10, 13 where Naboth is charged with cursing God and king). Abishai consistently advocates for punitive justice (cf. 2 Sam 16:9 during the Absalom flight). His position is legally defensible but politically tone-deaf in the moment of reconciliation.</p>",
    "22": "<p>David's rebuke — 'What business is this between you and me, you sons of Zeruiah? Why should you be my adversaries (<em>śāṭān</em>) today?' — is the only occurrence of <em>śāṭān</em> (adversary/satan) in the Samuel narrative. The word here means human adversary rather than supernatural being (as in Job 1:6 and Zech 3:1), but its use is deliberate: David frames Abishai's punitive zeal as working against the king's restoration agenda, making Abishai an obstacle rather than a supporter. The 'day of restoration' language frames clemency as politically appropriate.</p>",
    "23": "<p>David's oath of clemency to Shimei — 'You shall not die. And the king swore it to him' — is a formal royal oath. Solomon subsequently executes Shimei on a technicality (1 Kgs 2:36-46), providing him with grounds for execution that are legally distinct from the Absalom-rebellion offense. The tension between David's oath and Solomon's action raises the question of whether Solomon violates the spirit of David's pardon — the DH does not resolve this tension, leaving Shimei's fate ambiguous as an example of how political mercy and political security exist in permanent tension.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Mephibosheth's unkempt appearance — unwashed feet, untrimmed beard, unwashed clothes from the day of David's departure until his safe return — are the physical signs of mourning and fasting. In the Ziba episode (16:1-4), Ziba had claimed Mephibosheth was hoping Absalom's revolt would restore the Saulide kingdom. Mephibosheth's appearance of sustained mourning refutes this: he was in formal grief at David's forced departure, not celebrating his expected return. The physical evidence of sustained mourning is his primary defense.</p>",
    "25": "<p>David's question — 'Why did you not come with me, Mephibosheth?' — is judicial rather than simply curious. David had given Mephibosheth land and a place at his table (ch9); the failure to accompany the king required explanation. The question also implicitly acknowledges that a subject with Mephibosheth's disability might have legitimate difficulty following a king in flight — the question opens space for the explanation that follows.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Mephibosheth's defense — 'Ziba deceived me. I told him to saddle a donkey for me so I could ride with the king, but he slandered me to my lord the king' — is plausible given Ziba's demonstrated opportunism (16:1-4). The donkey as the necessary transport for a man with lame feet (<em>pĕṣê raglāyw</em>) is an important detail: without Ziba's donkey, Mephibosheth was physically unable to flee. Ziba exploited his disability to prevent his master from accompanying David and then slandered him.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'My lord the king is like an angel of God — do whatever seems right to you.' The comparison of the king to 'an angel of God' (<em>malʾāḵ hāʾelōhîm</em>) for his discernment appears also in 1 Sam 29:9 (Achish to David) and 2 Sam 14:17, 20 (the Tekoa woman to David). The formula is a compliment recognizing the king's divinely-given judicial wisdom — the ability to distinguish good from evil that characterizes both angelic beings and the ideal Davidic king (cf. the 'angel' of 2 Sam 24:16-17 who does execute judgment).</p>",
    "28": "<p>'All of my father's household deserved nothing but death from my lord the king' — Mephibosheth acknowledges the political liability of his Saulide lineage. Under ANE dynastic succession norms, the new king typically eliminated the previous dynasty's descendants (cf. Jehu's wholesale slaughter of Ahab's line, 2 Kgs 10:1-11). David's preservation of Mephibosheth was an act of extraordinary <em>ḥesed</em> (covenantal loyalty) to Jonathan's memory, departing from the political norm. Mephibosheth's acknowledgment of this grace is theologically significant: he knows his life is a gift, not a right.</p>",
    "29": "<p>David's resolution — dividing the land between Mephibosheth and Ziba — may reflect either judicial uncertainty (he cannot determine who is telling the truth) or political pragmatism (rewarding both parties' service during the rebellion). The decision is unsatisfying as jurisprudence: if Mephibosheth is telling the truth, the decision gives Ziba half the land he obtained by false witness. If Ziba is right, Mephibosheth gets more than he deserves. The ambiguity is left unresolved — a narrative reflection of the impossibility of perfect justice in complex political situations.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Mephibosheth's response — 'Let him have it all, since my lord the king has returned home safely' — is either genuine indifference to property in the joy of David's safe return (expressing the <em>ḥesed</em> relationship as more valuable than land) or a politically strategic concession that demonstrates his loyalty to David more than his attachment to the inheritance. Either reading honors the tradition: the Saulide who received grace responds with grace. The response functions as a vindication of David's original mercy in ch9.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Barzillai the Gileadite from Rogelim (location uncertain, possibly near Mahanaim in Transjordan) had supplied David during the Absalom refuge period (17:27-29 — Barzillai is listed with Shobi the Ammonite and Machir the Manassite as providers). His coming to the Jordan to escort the king is an act of personal loyalty that transcends his own interests — he is 80 years old (v32) and has nothing political to gain from the journey.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Barzillai's age (80 years) and wealth are both noted: he is a man of sufficient resources to have sustained David's army (17:28-29 lists provisions of wheat, barley, lentils, honey, curds, cheese, and sheep). The combination of wealth and age is significant: he is not acting from need of royal patronage but from loyalty. His age also explains the poignant limits he places on any future royal generosity (vv35-37) — he is too old to benefit from what David offers.</p>",
    "33": "<p>David's invitation — 'Cross over with me and I will look after you in Jerusalem' — is a formal offer of royal patronage: maintenance at the court, the honor of royal proximity, and the practical comforts of the palace. It is the same offer David made to Mephibosheth in ch9 (<em>ʾōḵal leḥem ʿal šulḥānî</em>, eating at the king's table). For an elderly man who had sustained the king in his crisis, the invitation is the highest possible honor.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Barzillai's response — 'How many years do I have left?' — opens a meditation on old age that is unique in the OT for its direct, unglamorous honesty. The question is both practical (he is 80) and philosophical: the remaining years of an elderly man do not justify uprooting from home and tomb. The Mesopotamian wisdom tradition has parallels in texts about the privileges and limitations of old age, but Barzillai's speech is more personal and less formulaic than those parallels.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'Can I tell the difference between what is pleasant and what is not? Can your servant taste what he eats or drinks? Can I still hear the voice of male and female singers?' The diminishment of the senses with age — taste, hearing, discernment — is Barzillai's inventory of what court life requires and what he can no longer provide or enjoy. 'Male and female singers' (<em>šārîm wĕšārôt</em>) was a specific feature of royal entertainment (cf. Eccl 2:8, where Solomon accumulates singers along with other luxuries). The honest accounting of limitation is a form of wisdom.</p>",
    "36": "<p>'Your servant will cross the Jordan with the king for a little way. Why should the king give me such a reward (<em>gəmûl</em>)?' <em>Gāmal</em> (to repay, recompense) is the word for covenant reciprocity — Barzillai frames the king's reward as more than he deserves for what he did. His question is rhetorical: the implied answer is that the king's generosity exceeds the service, and such excess reward places the recipient in an embarrassing dependency that Barzillai, in his wisdom, wishes to avoid.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Barzillai's request — 'Let your servant turn back, so that I may die in my own city by the tombs of my father and mother' — is the ancient Mediterranean's most universal wish: to die at home and be buried with one's ancestors. The grave of father and mother is not merely personal sentiment but the covenant community's continuity — the ancestral tombs represent the family's claim on the land (Gen 23, Abraham's purchase of Machpelah as a burial site establishes the principle). Barzillai nominates his son Chimham as his proxy recipient of royal patronage.</p>",
    "38": "<p>David's acceptance of Chimham as proxy recipient of royal patronage establishes a pattern: Chimham (possibly the same as Geruth Chimham near Bethlehem, Jer 41:17) receives what his father declined. The offer 'anything you ask of me I will do for you' is the royal blank-check formula that appears in the Solomonic narrative (1 Kgs 3:5) — here given to Barzillai before the Jordan crossing. The generosity extends to an open-ended promise, not merely the specific service of crossing.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The farewell — 'The king kissed Barzillai and blessed him' — uses the standard affective farewell vocabulary (kiss + blessing) that appears in covenant-parting scenes (Gen 31:55, Laban and Jacob; Exod 18:7, Moses and Jethro). The blessing (<em>bāraḵ</em>) from the king to the departing man is a formal act: the king's blessing is understood as effective, conferring divine favor on the recipient. Barzillai returns to 'his place' — his ancestral home, the stability that defines his character throughout this episode.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The king's arrival at Gilgal with all the people of Judah and half the people of Israel is the first explicit mention of the numerical imbalance that will produce the confrontation in vv41-43. Gilgal functions as the gathering point: historically it is the site of Joshua's first encampment (Josh 4:19), the place of Saul's coronation (1 Sam 11:15), and Samuel's rejection of Saul (1 Sam 15:12-33). David's return through Gilgal is therefore a theologically loaded crossing — the return to the beginning of the monarchy's history.</p>",
    "41": "<p>'Why did our brothers the men of Judah spirit you away (<em>gannaḇûḵā</em>)?' — The men of Israel use the theft-vocabulary (<em>gānab</em>, to steal) for Judah's appropriation of the restoration process. The accusation that Judah 'stole' the king by escorting him privately reflects the ancient political principle that the monarch belongs to all the tribes collectively — Judah's unilateral action was seen as breaking the covenant of shared ownership of the king. This is the political logic that will produce the permanent north-south split in 1 Kgs 12.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Judah's answer — 'Because the king is our kinsman (<em>qārôḇ ʾēlênû</em>)' — uses the kinship-basis defense: closer kinship to the king justifies closer association with his restoration. The 'have we eaten of the king's food?' defense argues that they received no economic benefit from the priority access. Both defenses are tribal rather than theological — neither side invokes YHWH's election of David or the Davidic covenant. The dispute is purely about honor, privilege, and tribal standing.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Israel's response — 'We have ten shares (<em>yādôt</em>) in the king, and in David we have more claim than you' — sets up the arithmetic of the future division: ten tribes (Israel) vs. one (Judah; Benjamin being ambiguous). <em>Yāḏ</em> (hand/share) means portion or stake — Israel claims a 10:1 advantage in the king's person by reason of numbers. The heated words ('the words of the men of Judah were harder than the words of Israel') fail to resolve the dispute and instead seed the Sheba revolt of ch20. The DH is transparent: the permanent north-south split has its roots here.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>'There happened to be there a worthless man (<em>ʾîš bəliyyaʿal</em>) named Sheba son of Bichri, a Benjaminite.' The characterization as <em>bəliyyaʿal</em> (covenant-outside man) immediately places Sheba in the category of those who operate outside covenant community norms (cf. Eli's sons, 1 Sam 2:12; Nabal, 1 Sam 25:25). Sheba's slogan — 'We have no portion in David, no inheritance in Jesse's son' — is virtually identical to the words in 1 Kgs 12:16 at the permanent north-south split under Rehoboam. The DH places this rebellion as the precursor to the eventual division; the political language is preserved as a type of the later rupture.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'All the men of Israel left David and followed Sheba son of Bichri, but the men of Judah stayed with their king from the Jordan to Jerusalem.' The precise tribal division — Israel with Sheba, Judah with David — maps exactly onto the eventual split of the monarchy. The fact that all the Israel-Judah tension of ch19's final verses (vv41-43) immediately converts into a military revolt shows how precarious David's political reconstruction was. The northern tribes' volatility reflects their historical ambivalence toward the Davidic monarchy throughout the DH.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David's treatment of the ten concubines who had been 'defiled' by Absalom (16:21-22) reflects the ANE legal principle that sexual access constitutes a property claim: Absalom's public intercourse with the concubines was a political declaration of kingship (a throne claim), making them irrevocably associated with him. David 'provided for them' but 'was not intimate with them' — they were maintained but sequestered, described as 'living as widows until the day of their death.' Their fate is simultaneously legally logical and humanly tragic.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David's appointment of Amasa to mobilize Judah within three days (replacing Joab as commander) is the military test of the political reconciliation announced in 19:13. Amasa's failure to mobilize on time (v5) may reflect the difficulty of replacing Joab's established command structure — Joab had built the army over decades; Amasa's authority was too new and too contested to command rapid compliance. The three-day deadline itself is urgently tight for mobilizing tribal forces.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Amasa's delay beyond the set time is the narrative's first hint that his appointment was not functionally successful. The reasons are not given: it may be logistical (the army was not his to command quickly), political (Joab loyalists dragging their feet), or personal (Amasa's own hesitation about confronting his former Absalom comrades). The delay gives Joab his opening — David turns to Abishai (Joab's brother) when Amasa fails, allowing Joab to re-insert himself into the command structure.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Sheba son of Bichri will do us more harm than Absalom' — David's assessment is geopolitically astute. Absalom's revolt was a palace coup with a temporary tribal following; Sheba's revolt is a tribal secession with a potentially permanent institutional basis. If Sheba reaches 'fortified cities' (<em>ʿārîm bĕṣurôt</em>) and establishes a northern military base, the division could become irreversible. The urgency reflects David's understanding that the political window for suppressing the revolt is short.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Joab's men, the Cherethites and Pelethites (the royal bodyguard of non-Israelite mercenaries — Cretan and Philistine troops), and 'all the warriors' march out of Jerusalem. The composition of the pursuing force reflects the Davidic military's multi-ethnic character: Joab's Israelite command structure, the foreign professional guard, and the elite warriors (the Thirty and their subordinates). This combination — native Israelite forces plus foreign mercenaries — was the standard composition of Near Eastern royal armies in this period.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Gibeon encounter provides the setting for Joab's murder of Amasa. 'Gibeon' is the treaty-city whose violation by Saul produces the famine in ch21 — the location resonates with the bloodguilt theme. The detail of Joab's sword 'falling out' (<em>wayyippōl</em>) is the narrator's way of presenting the murder as premeditated rather than accidental: Joab's right-hand grab of Amasa's beard (the greeting-kiss gesture) while holding the concealed sword is carefully choreographed violence dressed as affection.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Joab's 'Are you well, my brother?' (<em>hăšālôm ʾattāh ʾāḥî</em>) while grabbing Amasa by the beard for a kiss is the narrative's most explicitly ironic greeting. The beard-grab was the conventional posture for kissing a social equal or near-equal; it simultaneously immobilized Amasa. Joab's murder of Amasa mirrors his murder of Abner (3:27) — both killed by the sword thrust to the stomach in an apparent greeting. The pattern reveals Joab's habitual method: disguising lethal violence as social gesture.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Amasa did not notice the sword in Joab's hand' — the practical detail of the concealed weapon explains how the deception worked. The 'intestines poured out on the ground' (<em>šāpaḵ mēʿāyw ʾarṣāh</em>) is the same verb used of Judas's intestines in Acts 1:18 — a graphic detail preserved in both traditions of violent death. Joab then pursues Sheba 'without striking him a second blow' — the efficiency of the murder and the continuation of the mission narrative reinforce Joab's pragmatic brutality: Amasa's death is a tactical necessity, dispatched cleanly and immediately set aside.</p>",
    "11": "<p>One of Joab's men stands over Amasa's body and calls out a rallying cry: 'Whoever supports Joab and whoever is for David — follow Joab!' The public declaration establishes Joab's authority on the spot: the murder of the appointed commander is retroactively presented as an act of loyalty to David. The soldiers who might have hesitated at the killing of their new commander are given a framework (David's cause = Joab's cause) that makes compliance seem patriotic rather than complicity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Amasa's blood-soaked body lying in the road causes the troops to stop. The spectacle of the dead commander in the road is practically and symbolically problematic: practically, because it impedes troop movement; symbolically, because it is an unmourned body that implicates everyone who passes. The solution — moving the body off the road and covering it — is both practical and the minimum dignity owed a corpse. The 'covering a body' act (also done for Absalom in 18:17, where a pit covered him with stones) prevents the continuation of public exposure and dishonor.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Once Amasa is off the road, the men continue after Joab. The narrative's brisk continuation ('every man went on after Joab') suggests that the murder, while shocking, did not fracture the army's cohesion — Joab's authority, though illegitimate in terms of David's appointment, was functionally recognized by the men. This reflects a recurring DH pattern: institutional authority (David's appointment of Amasa) yields to demonstrated functional authority (Joab's command over the army's actual loyalty).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Sheba's route through the tribes of Israel to Abel Beth-maacah in the far north (modern Tell Abil el-Qamh, near the Dan/Hazor region) shows him seeking refuge in the peripheral northern areas furthest from Davidic authority. 'All the Bichrites assembled and followed him' — his own clan provides the core support; broader tribal support evaporated once Joab's army appeared. Abel Beth-maacah is mentioned also in 1 Kgs 15:20 (Ben-hadad's northern campaign) and 2 Kgs 15:29 (Tiglath-pileser's campaign) — always in the context of northern vulnerability.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The siege of Abel Beth-maacah employs a classic Near Eastern siege technique: a <em>sōlĕlāh</em> (siege ramp/embankment) against the outer wall. This is the same technique used in Assyrian and Babylonian siege warfare (visible in the Lachish reliefs of Sennacherib); the detail reflects the military technology of the period accurately. The army 'battered the wall' (<em>məšaḥîtîm baḥômāh</em>): the verb <em>šāḥat</em> (to destroy/damage) is used of the Babel builders and of YHWH's destruction of Sodom — siege warfare as cosmically resonant action.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The wise woman of Abel Beth-maacah is the third significant wise woman in the Samuel narratives (after the Tekoa woman of ch14 and Abigail of 1 Sam 25). Her authority to negotiate on behalf of the entire city reflects either a formal civic role or recognized personal wisdom that gave her standing to address Joab directly. The fact that Joab responds to her initiative — withdrawing from siege protocol to negotiate — indicates that such women had functional authority in their communities recognized even by external military commanders.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The woman's opening — 'Hear the words of your servant' (<em>šĕmaʿ nāʾ diḇrê ʾāmātĕḵā</em>) — uses the servant-address that appears throughout the Samuel narratives as the formulaic self-presentation of a petitioner before a superior (cf. Abigail to David, 1 Sam 25:24-25). The woman is demonstrating rhetorical knowledge: she frames herself in the culturally appropriate subordinate position while the content of what follows asserts the city's rights and YHWH's covenant claims.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'In the old days people used to say, &ldquo;Get your answer at Abel,&rdquo; and that is how they settled things.' The woman claims for Abel Beth-maacah the status of a traditional wisdom-center — a city known for its dispute-resolution capacity. This is consistent with the DH's presentation of wisdom as geographically distributed in cities of established reputation (cf. Tekoa as a place to seek wise counsel, 14:2). The city's reputation as a place of resolution gives the woman additional authority to negotiate: she represents not just herself but an institutional wisdom tradition.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'I am one of the peaceable and faithful (<em>šəlumê ʾĕmûnê</em>) in Israel. You are trying to destroy a city that is like a mother in Israel.' The woman appeals to the city's covenant status: 'peaceable and faithful' (<em>šālôm</em> and <em>ʾĕmûnāh</em>, the covenant-peace and covenant-faithfulness vocabulary) distinguishes her city from rebels. 'Mother in Israel' (<em>ʾēm bĕyiśrāʾēl</em>) — a unique title implying that the city has a nurturing, central role in the covenant community (cf. Judg 5:7, Deborah as 'mother in Israel'). Destroying such a city would be destroying the covenant network itself.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Joab's response — 'Far be it from me (<em>ḥālîlāh ḥālîlāh lî</em>), far be it indeed, that I should swallow up or destroy!' — uses the strongest Hebrew formula of rejection (<em>ḥālîlāh</em>, literally 'it be profaned,' the strongest negative oath). The double <em>ḥālîlāh</em> intensifies the denial; Joab presents himself as not wanting to destroy but only pursuing Sheba. This is technically accurate (the siege is about Sheba, not about Abel) but the siege of a city to force delivery of one man is itself potentially destructive — hence the woman's negotiation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Joab's demand — 'Hand over this one man, and I will withdraw from the city' — resolves the military situation through a principle of proportionate response: one guilty man's life in exchange for the city's preservation. The theological background is Abraham's negotiation over Sodom (Gen 18:23-32), where the innocent and guilty are distinguished. Here the distinction is simpler: Sheba is the rebel and the city is not — delivering the rebel is the minimal act that preserves covenant status. The woman's wisdom is in identifying this solution before Joab states it.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The woman 'in her wisdom went to all the people' (<em>ḇĕḥoḵmātāh ʾel kol hāʿām</em>) — the wisdom is applied communally, not just in negotiation with Joab. The city council makes the collective decision to deliver Sheba; the woman is the mediating agent who brings the wisdom to bear on the community decision. The result: Sheba's head thrown over the wall, Joab blows the trumpet (the signal of cessation of hostilities), and the army disperses. The economy of resolution — one head over a wall ends the entire revolt — is the narrative's point about the proportionality of the woman's wisdom.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The administrative list that follows the Sheba revolt (vv23-26) parallels the earlier list in 8:16-18 — the same positions but with some personnel changes. Joab is confirmed as commander of all Israel's army (his de facto role throughout the Absalom and Sheba revolts now formally recognized despite David's earlier attempt to replace him with Amasa). Benaiah over the Cherethites and Pelethites (the royal guard) confirms the structure of the Davidic military: the regular army under Joab, the professional guard under Benaiah.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Adoram over forced labor (<em>hammas</em>) is the first reference in the Samuel narrative to the <em>mas</em> (corvée labor) system that will become a central grievance against Solomon (1 Kgs 4:6; 5:14; 12:18 — the Rehoboam-Adoram incident where the corvée officer is stoned to death). David's introduction of forced labor represents a significant step toward the state-building practices that Solomon will expand to alienating levels. The inclusion of this detail in the administrative list is an early warning of the system that will eventually fracture the kingdom.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The secretary (<em>sōpēr</em>, Sheva here vs. Seraiah in 8:17 — a scribal variant) and the recorder (<em>mazkîr</em>, Jehoshaphat son of Ahilud) round out the civil administration. The <em>sōpēr</em> kept official records and drafted royal correspondence; the <em>mazkîr</em> (from <em>zākar</em>, to remember) was probably the royal herald or chronicler who maintained oral and written records. The parallel Mesopotamian titles — <em>ṭupšarru</em> (scribe) and <em>ālik pāni</em> (herald/announcer) — suggest David's court was modeled on the administrative structures of the surrounding states.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Ira the Jairite was David's personal priest (<em>kōhēn lĕdāwid</em>).' A 'Jairite' (from Jair of Gilead?) holding the position of royal chaplain alongside the established Zadok/Abiathar priesthood suggests either a supplementary priestly role or that the Jairite is a different tribal/regional designation. Significantly, this verse appears only in the post-revolt administrative list (not in 8:18's list, which has David's sons as priests). The reorganization after two revolts apparently included new appointments to the royal household staff.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>The three-year famine and David's inquiry of YHWH opens a series of appendices (chs21-24) that the DH has gathered outside the strict chronological narrative. The connection of famine to bloodguilt is a standard ancient Near Eastern theological principle: corporate sin defiles the land and disrupts agricultural productivity (cf. the Achan episode, Josh 7; the Hittite Plague Prayers of Mursilis II, where the king inquires of divine oracles about what sin caused the plague afflicting his kingdom). YHWH's answer — 'there is bloodguilt on Saul and on his house, because he put the Gibeonites to death' — cites an offense not narrated elsewhere in the OT.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Gibeonites were 'not Israelites but a remnant of the Amorites' — the same characterization as the Hittites, Hivites, and other Canaanite peoples who survived the conquest. The Josh 9 treaty with Gibeon was made by the Israelite leaders who 'did not inquire of the LORD' (Josh 9:14) but were nonetheless legally binding because oaths were sacred. 'Saul had sought to kill them in his zeal for the people of Israel and Judah' — this Saulide pogrom against Gibeon is unnarrated but assumed; it may be connected to 1 Sam 22:6-19 (Saul's massacre of the Nob priests, whom the Gibeonites may have been associated with).</p>",
    "3": "<p>David's question — 'What should I do for you? How shall I make atonement (<em>kāpar</em>) so that you will bless the inheritance of YHWH?' — uses the priestly vocabulary of expiation (<em>kāpar</em>, to cover/atone) in a non-sacrificial legal context. The 'inheritance of YHWH' (<em>naḥălat YHWH</em>) is the land of Israel — the land that belongs to YHWH and whose productivity depends on its purity (Lev 18:28: 'the land vomited out its inhabitants' because of their defilement). David is asking what legal act will restore covenant harmony and end the famine.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'It is not a question of silver or gold between us and Saul or his house, and it is not for us to put any man to death in Israel.' The Gibeonites' initial response refuses two of the three standard reparation options in ancient Near Eastern law: monetary compensation and blood-feud (the wronged party taking their own revenge). The third option — execution by the authorized party, the king — is what they will request. Their framing of the issue as 'not our right to put to death' establishes that the execution they will request must be carried out by royal authority, not private vengeance.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Gibeonites' description of Saul's offense — 'the man who destroyed us and planned to annihilate us so that we would have no place anywhere in Israel' — uses the vocabulary of genocidal intent (<em>kālāh</em>, to finish/annihilate; <em>ʾăšer dimmāh lanû</em>, who plotted against us). This is legal testimony, not merely complaint: they are establishing the seriousness of the violation that justifies their demand. The intent to eliminate a protected people from 'all the territory of Israel' constitutes the maximum violation of the covenant's protective obligations.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Let seven of his male descendants be handed over to us, so we may hang them before YHWH at Gibeah of Saul, at the mountain of YHWH.' The number seven (the complete set) and the location (Gibeah of Saul, Saul's own city) are both significant: seven is the covenant-number (the number of sacrifice and completeness); Gibeah of Saul as the execution site makes the judgment fall on Saul's own inheritance. The phrase 'before YHWH' (<em>lĕYHWH</em>) frames the execution as a judicial act with divine sanction — not murder but covenant-enforced execution of bloodguilt.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'But the king spared Mephibosheth son of Jonathan son of Saul, because of the oath sworn before YHWH between David and Jonathan.' David's exemption of Mephibosheth invokes the Jonathan covenant (1 Sam 18:3; 20:42; 23:18) as the legal basis for the exception. This is legally precise: the oath covered Jonathan's household, which includes Mephibosheth. The <em>ḥesed</em> obligation to Jonathan overrides the bloodguilt obligation to the Gibeonites — covenant loyalty takes precedence, and the specific covenant oath determines who falls within its protection.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Armoni and Mephibosheth (a different Mephibosheth from Jonathan's son — the son of Rizpah, Saul's concubine) plus the five sons of Merab (daughter of Saul) represent the seven required by the Gibeonites. The decision to include Merab's sons (through Adriel the Meholathite, 1 Sam 18:19) extends the bloodguilt to descendants of Saul's daughter. The principle that corporate guilt passes through the male descendants of the offender is consistent with ANE legal traditions; the exclusion of Mephibosheth shows it is not absolute but subject to specific covenant exemptions.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'He hanged them on the mountain before YHWH; all seven fell together.' The timing — 'at the beginning of harvest (<em>bittĕḥillat qāṣîr</em>), at the beginning of barley harvest' — links the execution to the agricultural calendar: the harvest season is exactly when rain is needed. The execution at the start of the harvest is therefore a statement of faith that YHWH will end the famine in response to the act of expiation. In ANE thought, ritual acts at critical agricultural moments were understood to affect the land's productivity.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Rizpah daughter of Aiah's vigil over the bodies — spreading sackcloth on a rock and keeping watch from the beginning of the barley harvest until the autumn rains fell — is one of the most powerful acts in the Samuel narrative. 'She did not let the birds of the sky touch them by day, or the wild animals by night' is the most minimal possible burial-proxy: she cannot bury them (forbidden during the period of expiation) but she can protect them from desecration. The sackcloth on the rock is both her mourning garment and her shelter for the months of vigil. Rizpah's sustained maternal grief has no parallel in the OT for duration and setting.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'David was told what Rizpah daughter of Aiah, Saul's concubine, had done.' The narrative is explicit that it was Rizpah's action that prompted David's next response (vv12-14 — burying Saul's bones). The cause-and-effect here is deliberate: Rizpah's grief-vigil for the executed men catalyzes David's act of <em>ḥesed</em> toward the entire Saulide house. Rizpah, who has no political power, changes the king's actions through the moral weight of her sustained mourning. This is one of the DH's clearest examples of prophetic critique through narrative rather than oracle.</p>",
    "12": "<p>David retrieves the bones of Saul and Jonathan from Jabesh-gilead, where the men of Jabesh-gilead had secretly taken them after rescuing them from the Philistine walls of Beth-shan (1 Sam 31:11-13). Jabesh-gilead's loyalty to Saul (they were the city he saved in his first military victory, 1 Sam 11) had extended beyond his death to the protection of his remains. David's retrieval acknowledges both Jabesh-gilead's faithfulness and his own obligation to Saul as YHWH's first anointed.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'He brought up from there the bones of Saul and Jonathan, and they also gathered the bones of those who had been hanged' — the combining of Saul/Jonathan's bones with the seven executed men is the narrative's final act of reconciliation: the king who had violated the Gibeonite covenant and his seven punished descendants are all buried together with full honor. The gathering of the bones follows the principle that exposure of the dead is the maximum dishonor and that proper burial, even delayed, restores dignity.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'They buried the bones of Saul and his son Jonathan in Zela of Benjamin, in the tomb of his father Kish.' The burial in Kish's tomb in Zela (a Benjaminite location, exact site uncertain) returns Saul and Jonathan to their tribal ancestral burial ground. 'After that, God answered prayer for the land' (<em>wayyi''ātar ʾĕlōhîm lāʾāreṣ ʾaḥărê kēn</em>) — the grammatically precise statement that divine response to prayer followed the burial confirms the theological principle: the bloodguilt that caused the famine has been atoned; the land can now receive the rains. The narrative closes the bloodguilt-famine-atonement cycle with formal divine response.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The transition to the Philistine war episodes (vv15-22) is marked by 'there was war again.' These episodes are thematically connected to the giant-killing tradition of 1 Sam 17 and functionally serve as closure for the Rephaim theme: the last descendants of the Anakim/Rephaim (the giant peoples of Canaan, Deut 2:11, 20; 3:11) fall to David's servants. David's own near-death in battle (v17: he grows weary, and Ishbi-benob nearly kills him) is a final narrative mark of his mortality — the aging king can no longer fight as he once did.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Ishbi-benob is described as 'one of the descendants of the giants (<em>yĕlîdê hārāpāh</em>)' — the <em>rāpāh</em> (Raphah) being the ancestral giant figure associated with the Rephaim tradition (cf. 21:18, 20, 22). His bronze spearhead weighing 300 shekels (~3.4 kg) is comparable to Goliath's iron spear with a 600-shekel head (1 Sam 17:7) — the weaponry marks his class as superhuman opponent. The near-killing of David establishes the stakes: had Abishai not intervened, the Davidic line and its covenant would have been cut off.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Then David's men swore to him, &ldquo;You must not go out to battle with us anymore, so that the lamp (<em>nēr</em>) of Israel will not be extinguished.&rdquo;' The 'lamp of Israel' formula appears as a royal title in 1 Kgs 11:36; 15:4; 2 Kgs 8:19 — the continuation of the Davidic line called a lamp that YHWH promised not to extinguish. Here it is used not as a promise about descendants but as a warning about David himself: he is the lamp, and his death in battle would extinguish Israel's light. The protective restriction placed on the king is the ANE convention of royal protection from front-line combat — the king's death in battle being potentially catastrophic for the army's morale and the covenant's continuity.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The four subsequent Philistine giant-battles (vv18-22) form a mini-catalog parallel to the Three/Thirty warriors of ch23. At Gob, Sibbecai the Hushathite kills Saph — the same Sibbechai listed as Mebunnai/Sibbechai in 23:27 and the monthly rotation list (1 Chr 27:11). The geographic detail of Gob is uncertain; the Chronicler's parallel (1 Chr 20:4) calls it Gezer.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Elhanan son of Jaare-oregim the Bethlehemite struck down Goliath the Gittite, whose spear shaft was like a weaver's rod.' The problem: 1 Sam 17 attributes Goliath's killing to David, while this verse attributes it to Elhanan. 1 Chr 20:5 'corrects' the text: 'Elhanan son of Jair struck down Lahmi the brother of Goliath.' The Chronicler's version attempts harmonization; the Samuel MT preserves the more difficult reading. Most scholarship holds that either: (1) there were two 'Goliaths' as a Philistine title; (2) the Elhanan tradition is older and the David story absorbed it; or (3) 'Elhanan' was another name for David (a throne name). The textual problem is among the most discussed in OT scholarship.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'There was another battle at Gath, where there was a man of great size who had six fingers on each hand and six toes on each foot, twenty-four in all' — polydactyly as a marker of the giant class. Extra digits appear in ANE literature as a supernatural sign; in archaeological finds, polydactyly is a recessive genetic trait more common in isolated populations. The detail serves to characterize the Rephaim/giant class as physically anomalous from birth — their large size is not merely hereditary but marked by physical deviation from the human norm.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Jonathan son of Shimei (David's brother) kills the polydactyl giant of Gath. 'When he taunted Israel (<em>ḥārēp</em>), Jonathan son of Shimei struck him down' — the same taunting (<em>ḥārap</em>) vocabulary that Goliath used (1 Sam 17:10, 25, 26, 36) and that Eleazar faced at Pas-dammim (23:9). The giant's defiance of Israel is the standard provocation for the champion-battle tradition; David's nephew replays the Goliath dynamic at the family level. David's family defeating Goliath-class enemies is an inclusio: the Goliath tradition begins and ends with the house of Jesse.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'These four were descendants of the giants in Gath (<em>yĕlûdê hārāpāh bəgat</em>), and they fell by the hand of David and his servants.' The summary closes the Rephaim theme: the last of the giant peoples are defeated by the Davidic court. The theological implication is that the conquest is now complete — the Rephaim/Anakim whom Joshua had reduced but not eliminated (Josh 11:22: 'None of the Anakim was left in the land of the Israelites; only in Gaza, in Gath, and in Ashdod did some remain') are now wholly removed by David's warriors. The incomplete conquest is finished under the Davidic monarchy.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', '2samuel')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2samuel', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'2samuel mkt-context ch19-21: wrote {total} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
